                <b>Where does a dress code apply?</b><br/>
                A strict dress code applies on any tour that enters a mosque. The tour description will clearly indicate this and we will specify the dress code in the “important information” section of the tour page. In order to gain access to these sites, both men and women are asked to take off their shoes (you will put them in a plastic bag, provided by the Mosque, and bring them with you). Both are also asked to have their knees and shoulders covered. Women are asked to wear a head covering when entering. Please bring a scarf with you. Walks of Turkey cannot be held responsible for denied entry due to improper dress.
                <br/><br/>
                <b>Can I shop during your tours?</b><br/>
                We have not built free shopping time into our tours because we have found that it disrupts the flow of the tour, with some guests delaying their return and others not wanting to shop at all. We will never take you to carpet shops or any other stores where the staff will promote their products. During tours of the bazaars, our guides will be happy to provide you with shopping and bargaining tips, however we have not built in any unaccompanied shopping time in our tour itineraries.
                <br/><br/>
                <b>Do sites close on religious holidays?</b><br/>
                Sites tend to have reduced opening hours on religious holidays and some sites are closed on Friday mornings until 1pm/1.30pm. You will not be able to book a tour on our website on a date in which one of the sites is scheduled to be closed. That said, the Blue Mosque is subject to unforeseen closures during special celebrations and festivities. These closures are generally only announced a few days prior. If this occurs during your visit, we will spend more time at other sites. Your guide will still give you full information on the mosque should you wish to visit this on your own at a later occasion. We are unable to provide refunds or discounts but it is free to visit the Blue Mosque.
                <br/><br/>
                <b>Why is there no Skip the Line Access at the Blue Mosque?</b><br/>
                The Blue Mosque is a religious site and entrance is free. There is no system in place to reserve priority access as we do at sites like Hagia Sophia. As a tourist, one can only access the site at specific times, in between prayer times which happen five times a day, with the first call to prayer at sunrise and the last one at nightfall. The mosque closes for 90 minutes for each prayer time.
                <br/><br/>
                <b>Why do you not enter the Galata Tower?</b><br/>
                The Galata Tower does not offer the possibility of reserving Skip the Line Access and often the lines are very long. Furthermore there is nothing to visit inside the tower, other than the cafe. The reason to enter the tower is exclusively for the view of the city. On our tours, we thus walk you to see the tower and then walk around the corner to a rooftop terrace for the same view over the Old City.
